  "text": "TLR4 plays a key role in the development of innate defence mechanisms and adaptive immunity against pathogens, and Myd88 acts as an intermediate linker for inflammatory motility [CITATION_1] . Compared to the control group ( Figure 5A ), LPS stimulation significantly upregulated TLR4 and Myd88 protein expression, indicating that LPS induced TLR4 and Myd88 activation. However, betaine treatment effectively inhibited TLR4 and Myd88 protein expression in N9 microglial cells. Given that Myd88 signalling mediates the NF-κB pathway, we evaluated the activation of the NF-κB pathway by western blot analysis. As shown in Figure 5B -D, LPS stimulation resulted in the phosphorylation of IκB kinase (IKK-β), IκB-α, and NF-κB p65 but did not affecting IKK-β, IκB-α and NF-κBp-65 their activity expression. However, betaine treatment decreased the expression of p-IKK-β, p-IκB-α, and p-NF-κB p65. These results indicated that betaine inhibited the LPS-induced activation of the TLR4/NF-κB pathways in N9 microglial cells in vitro. MIDO was used as a positive control. (B-D) Determination of IKK-β, P-IKK-β, IκΒ-α, P-IκΒ-α, NF-κΒ, and p-NF-κΒ protein levels by western blot analysis. MIDO was used as a positive control. Data are presented as the means ± SEM of three independent experiments. The control group included untreated cells. Untreated cells served as a control group. # p < 0.05, compared to the control group; * p < 0.05 and ** p < 0.01, compared to the LPS-treated group.",
